<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Source_Release"> Source Release </span></h2>
<p>You can download the source tarball here:
</p>
<pre><a class="external free" href="https://sourceforge.net/projects/libfirm/files/libfirm/">https://sourceforge.net/projects/libfirm/files/libfirm/</a>
</pre>
<p>Afterwards a usual <tt>./configure &amp;&amp; make</tt> will do the rest.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Ubuntu"> Ubuntu </span></h2>
<p>An experimental repository for Ubuntu karmic is available, which contains a libfirm-dev package.
The packages were not checked by Ubuntu devs, so use <b>at own risk</b>.
Add the following to your sources.list:
</p>
<pre>deb <a class="external free" href="http://pp.info.uni-karlsruhe.de/~zwinkau/repo/Ubuntu">http://pp.info.uni-karlsruhe.de/~zwinkau/repo/Ubuntu</a> karmic IPD
deb-src <a class="external free" href="http://pp.info.uni-karlsruhe.de/~zwinkau/repo/Ubuntu">http://pp.info.uni-karlsruhe.de/~zwinkau/repo/Ubuntu</a> karmic IPD
</pre>
<p>The reason for the libfirm-dev package is mostly as a build dependency for <a class="external text" href="http://cparser.sourceforge.net/">cparser</a>, which is also in the repository.
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Git_Source"> Git Source </span></h2>
{% code "bash" %}
$ git clone http://pp.info.uni-karlsruhe.de/git/libfirm.git
{% endcode %}
<p>Now you can use make to build libfirm and cparser:
</p>
{% code "bash" %}
$ make
{% endcode %}
{% endblock %}
